{
  "masechta": "Yevamot",
  "daf": 66,
  "amud": "b",
  "macro_segments": [
    {
      "title": "Slaves of a wife who became chalalah: can they eat terumah?",
      "display_title": "Slaves & Chalalah",
      "timestamp": "00:22",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Introduction: nichsei milug vs. nichsei tzon barzel and the mashna's case",
          "display_title": "Setup: Property Types",
          "timestamp": "00:22"
        },
        {
          "title": "Ravina's principle: kinyan ochel maachil (only a kinyan that eats can feed)",
          "display_title": "Kinyan Ochel Maachil",
          "timestamp": "05:19"
        },
        {
          "title": "Rava's answer: slaves can eat in principle, but gezeira to discourage forbidden marriage",
          "display_title": "Rava's Gezeira",
          "timestamp": "05:44"
        },
        {
          "title": "Rav Ashi's answer: gezeira lest she feed slaves after husband's death",
          "display_title": "Rav Ashi: Gezeira",
          "timestamp": "07:04"
        },
        {
          "title": "Rav Ashi's refined case: almanah kohenet who might rely on original status as bat kohen",
          "display_title": "Almanah Kohenet Case",
          "timestamp": "07:41"
        },
        {
          "title": "Gemara resolves: same gezeira applies to all cases of widow to avoid confusion",
          "display_title": "Uniform Gezeira",
          "timestamp": "11:41"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Nichsei tzon barzel: does the wife retain title or does he own them?",
      "display_title": "Tzon Barzel Ownership",
      "timestamp": "12:21",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "The case: woman brings assessed property to husband as dowry; on divorce, can she reclaim objects or only their value?",
          "display_title": "The Dispute",
          "timestamp": "12:21"
        },
        {
          "title": "Rav Yehuda: she can reclaim objects (midat rachminut—benefit of her father's house)",
          "display_title": "Rav Yehuda Position",
          "timestamp": "14:34"
        },
        {
          "title": "Rav Ami: husband owns; he bears loss and gains benefit, so title transfers",
          "display_title": "Rav Ami Position",
          "timestamp": "15:09"
        },
        {
          "title": "Gemara tests: renting analogy—liability for loss insufficient; but nichsei tzon barzel is higher degree of responsibility",
          "display_title": "Renting Analogy Test",
          "timestamp": "18:24"
        },
        {
          "title": "Gemara concludes: maybe not ownership, but responsibility high enough that slaves eat terumah",
          "display_title": "Responsibility vs. Owner…",
          "timestamp": "20:02"
        },
        {
          "title": "Baraita evidence: husband cannot sell dowry property; Rabban Gamliel voids sale to buyers",
          "display_title": "Baraita: No Sale Right",
          "timestamp": "25:45"
        },
        {
          "title": "Rava rules like Rav Yehuda: she is entitled to retrieve dowry objects",
          "display_title": "Rava's Ruling",
          "timestamp": "27:39"
        },
        {
          "title": "Story: cloak used as shroud for corpse; status changes and wife loses rights despite being entitled to reclaim",
          "display_title": "Shroud Story",
          "timestamp": "29:46"
        },
        {
          "title": "Rav Kahana clarifies: even if entitled to reclaim, she must actually collect; until then under husband's control",
          "display_title": "Collection Requirement",
          "timestamp": "31:02"
        },
        {
          "title": "Case: woman brought two vessels worth 1000, now worth 2000; she retrieves both and pays increase",
          "display_title": "Two Vessels Example",
          "timestamp": "33:55"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Unborn fetus (ubar) and slave terumah: does fetus take inheritance share and prevent slaves from eating?",
      "display_title": "Fetus & Slave Terumah",
      "timestamp": "37:00",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Case: kohen dies leaving pregnant wife; slaves cannot eat terumah because of fetus's share",
          "display_title": "Ubar Posel",
          "timestamp": "37:00"
        },
        {
          "title": "Rabbi Yossi's position: ubar invalidates and does not feed (posel veeino maachil)",
          "display_title": "Rabbi Yossi's Principle",
          "timestamp": "38:43"
        },
        {
          "title": "Possible reason A: fetus is non-kohen (follows mother's status) so slaves can't eat through him",
          "display_title": "Reason A: Non-Kohen",
          "timestamp": "40:35"
        },
        {
          "title": "Possible reason B: only born persons can have others eat on their behalf (yalud maachil)",
          "display_title": "Reason B: Yalud Maachil",
          "timestamp": "41:24"
        },
        {
          "title": "Sages' counter-position: if there are born children, they eat by virtue of them; fetus has no estate share until birth",
          "display_title": "Sages: No Fetus Share",
          "timestamp": "44:41"
        },
        {
          "title": "Assumption 1: fetus already takes title to inheritance; Assumption 2: can't eat while unborn",
          "display_title": "Two Assumptions",
          "timestamp": "44:52"
        },
        {
          "title": "Shmuel presents sages' position but himself sides with Rabbi Yossi via tradition of Shemaya and Avtalyon",
          "display_title": "Shmuel's Stance",
          "timestamp": "47:09"
        },
        {
          "title": "Shmuel proves fetus can take title: one can transfer property to unborn, so inheritance applies too",
          "display_title": "Fetus Can Inherit",
          "timestamp": "48:03"
        },
        {
          "title": "Scenarios: children only (both eat); pregnant only (neither eat); children + pregnant (mother eats via children, but his slaves blocked by fetus)",
          "display_title": "All Scenarios",
          "timestamp": "51:18"
        },
        {
          "title": "Rabbi Yishmael bar Rabbi Yossi: daughter can feed mother but not son (unclear meaning, to be clarified)",
          "display_title": "R. Yishmael Position",
          "timestamp": "53:39"
        },
        {
          "title": "Rabbi Shimon ben Yochai: males all eat, females none (concern about finding male fetus)",
          "display_title": "R. Shimon Position",
          "timestamp": "53:52"
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
